As an AI language model, I cannot run MATLAB code directly. However, I can provide you with the MATLAB code that you can use to solve the problem. You can copy and paste this code into your MATLAB environment to obtain the results.

Here's the MATLAB code to plot the phase space trajectory of the particle:

```MATLAB
% Rikitake system parameters
a = 0.2;
b = 5.7;
c = 0.6;
d = 3.5;

% Initial condition
x0 = 1;
y0 = 1;

% Time interval
tspan = [0, 800];

% Rikitake system function
rik_sys = @(t, X) [a * (X(2) - X(1) * X(2) - X(1) * X(3));
                   b * (X(1) - X(1) * X(2) - X(3));
                   c * X(1) - d * X(3)];

% Solve the system using ode45
[~, X] = ode45(rik_sys, tspan, [x0; y0; 0]);

% Plot the phase space trajectory
figure;
plot3(X(:,1), X(:,2), X(:,3));
xlabel('x');
ylabel('y');
zlabel('z');
title('Phase space trajectory of the Rikitake system');
grid on;
```

To calculate the Lyapunov exponent, you can use the following code:

```MATLAB
% Number of iterations
N = 10000;

% Perturbation
delta = 1e-9;

% Initialize variables
sum_log = 0;
X_perturbed = [x0 + delta; y0; 0];

% Iterate the system
for i = 1:N
    [~, X_temp] = ode45(rik_sys, [0, 1], X_perturbed(:, end));
    X_perturbed = [X_perturbed, X_temp(:, end)];
    sum_log = sum_log + log(norm(X_temp(:, end) - X_perturbed(:, end - 1)) / delta);
end

% Calculate the Lyapunov exponent
lyapunov_exponent = sum_log / N;
```

Run this code in your MATLAB environment to obtain the Lyapunov exponent for the given parameter values.
